        <name>L7.2 Q7 T-F</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Decide if the following statements are correct or wrong:
  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;&lt;li&gt;If \( p &amp;gt;1\), then \( \displaystyle{\int_1^\infty \frac{1}{x^p} dx = \frac{1}{p-1}.}\)
    &lt;p&gt;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt; If \( p &amp;lt;1\), then \(\displaystyle{ \int_0^1 \frac{1}{x^p} dx = \frac{1}{1-p}.}\)

  &lt;p&gt;[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;In the first case&amp;nbsp;\( \displaystyle{\int_1^\infty \frac{1}{x^p} dx} =&amp;nbsp; \displaystyle{ \lim_{t\to \infty} \int_1^t \frac{1}{x^p} dx} =&amp;nbsp;\displaystyle{ \lim_{t\to \infty}&amp;nbsp;[x^{-p+1}/(-p+1)]_1^t}\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;So we have \( \lim_{t \to \infty} t^{-p+1}/(-p+1)-1/(-p+1)\) and since \(p&amp;gt;1\) we have \(-p+1&amp;lt;0\) so \(t^{-p+1} \to 0\) as \(t \to \infty\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;The other case should be similar except we have \(\displaystyle{ \lim_{t\to 0+} \int_t^1 \frac{1}{x^p} dx}\) and of course \(p&amp;lt;1\) so that \(-p+1&amp;gt;0\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;br&gt;

&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
